are searching business design fashion music health life sports home marketing children mandarin oriental hotel group a  insead published by guset user   pages    description mandarin oriental was known as an asiabased hotel group with a strong balance sheet significant ownership of its properties which typically served highend  mandarin oriental hotel group athis case was written by gabriel szulanski professor of strategy at insead jessica zee research associate andjenifer raver research associate it is intended to be used as a basis for class discussion rather than to illustrateeither effective or ineffective handling of an administrative situationfinancial support from capgemini consulting is gratefully acknowledgedcopyright   inseadto order copies of insead cases see details on the back cover copies may not be made without permissionintroductionwhen edouard ettedgui took over as chief executive officer of mandarin oriental hotelgroup in  one of the questions he asked himself was “how can i add value to thiscompany” looking at the business portfolio of the  mandarin oriental properties at thetime he knew he had inherited a collection of firstclass hotels that were consistently ratedamong the top three in their respective destinations including hong kong and bangkokmandarin oriental was known as an asiabased hotel group with a strong balance sheetsignificant ownership of its properties which typically served highend corporate executivesand an extraordinary brand reputation in asia where  out of its  hotels were locatedhowever it was also clear that the group had “a very limited brand profile outside of asia” atthat point in timeettedgui felt that more could be done with the group by transforming it into an internationalbrand and he had the ultimate aspiration of creating a brand that stood for ‘legendary’ hotelssucceeding in key cities like new york london paris tokyo and hong kong would have ahuge impact on any luxury brand but for mandarin oriental it would make future expansionwithin or beyond asia even more likely and impactful he also believed that in the futureleisure as opposed to business guests would define the brandwith this vision in mind he began working with his key executives to craft the plan forbringing the brand to the rest of the world in  ettedgui and his team launched thegroup’s very first global advertising campaign for the brand previous advertising effortswere managed by and focused on individual hotel properties the company hired mcsaatchi to design the “shehe’s a fan” campaign which was shot by the world famousphotographer and british royal lord lichfield the campaign elegantly connected thegroup’s wellrecognised symbol – the fan – with international celebrities such as michelleyeoh im pei and lance armstrong who regularly stayed at the hotels and were fans of thegroupthe  million campaign focused on the usa and western europe the two markets thataccounted “for the majority of high net worth individuals’ wealth” according to the worldwealth report  by capgemini and merrill lynch the campaign’s core theme focusingon the brand as a whole rather than individual hotel properties made an enormous impact forthe group and was an immense success with one of the highest recall rates magazines with aluxury leisure focus such as architectural digest and condé nast traveler us beganregularly featuring the brand and its properties as a result it became well known to theluxury leisure travel community and among luxury hotel developers mandarin oriental international limited annual report  irasia httplistcosgmandarinannualannualpdf  november  john witt interview by jessica zee and gabriel szulanski insead  october  john witt interview by jessica zee and gabriel szulanski insead  october  “the fan club” mandarin oriental hotel group website http httpwwwmohgcomourfans  november  “merrill lynch  gemini consulting world wealth report ”  october  capgemini website  httpwwwcapgeminicomresourcesthoughtleadershipworldwealthreport  november copyright   insead  recognising that the us was an extremely important market while adhering to the premise ofmaintaining brand exclusivity by focusing solely on key cities and resort destinationsmandarin oriental hotel group viewed new york the centre stage as an obvious locationthrough which to expand into north america because the market here offered a luxury basethat was large and wide enough to establish its very own flagship property – mandarinoriental new york – and potentially a second property henceforth the mission was todecide how best to define translate and project mandarin oriental’s legendary hospitalityexperience in new york a destination which was not only far removed in terms of distancebut also culturethe industryaccording to the world travel  tourism council travel and tourism accounted for billion  of global gdp and  million jobs worldwide in  the industry wasimpacted by the asian economic crisis in  particularly in asia where declining visitorarrivals resulted in fierce price competition quantified as an economic engine for developedand developing economies worldwide travel and tourism was estimated to grow from  in to  in  in the long run its economic contribution was expected to grow to billion  of global gdp in  supporting  million jobsthe global hotel industry generated total revenues of over  billion in  and waspredicted to grow at  to  billion in  projected industry revenue was estimatedto exceed  billion by  geographically diverse the hotel industry servicedconsumers around the globe with  million hotel rooms worldwide as of  and manythousands more under development the luxury hotel segment was unique in the global hotel industry it could be definedprimarily by premium room rates a clientele with high average net worth and comprehensiveluxury amenities and facilities such as spa services celebrity chefrun restaurants luxuriousdesign aesthetics and most importantly an emphasis on offering superior service for apositive customer “experience”the key players in the luxury hotel sector as defined by brand position number of rooms andbusiness models included accor hospitality sofitel four seasons mandarin orientalstarwood hotels  resorts st regis the peninsula hotels and marriott hotels ritzcarlton among them starwood accor and marriott had brand portfolios covering multiplecustomer segments from economy to luxury while four seasons peninsula and mandarinoriental had established individual collections of luxury hotels under their respective flagshipbrands most of the key incumbents adopted an assetlight strategy with the exception ofpeninsula and mandarin oriental which both owned the majority of their properties all “global tourism forecasts for ”  may  world travel  tourism council website httpwwwhospitalitynetorgnewshtml  september  mark lomanto smith travel research  black collegian website httpwwwblack collegiancomcareerindustryreportsindrelishesthshtml  september  “global hotels  motels industry profile” november  datamonitor website wwwmarketresearchcom  september  pizam abraham international encyclopaedia of hospitality management butterworthheinemann publishers april copyright   insead  except accor and mandarin oriental had been operating one or more luxury hotels in newyork prior to mandarin orientalthe first mandarin oriental hotel was built in  in hong kong previously themandarin while the mandarin oriental bangkok previously the oriental was acquired in these two “legendary” hotels widely recognised by respected travel associations andpublications gave rise to mandarin oriental hotel group an international hotel investmentand management company whose strategic objective was to be recognised as the world’s bestluxury hotel group in ettedgui’s words the group was in the business of running“legendary hotels not fivestar hotels” in his view “a legendary hotel does not need arating system because its standing is obvious”by  the group employed some  people and operated  luxury hotels worldwidegenerating revenues of  million an increase of  over  out of the  hotelsmandarin oriental san francisco and mandarin oriental hyde park london were the onlytwo operating outside asia mandarin oriental hyde park was known for its history because“members of the royal family have always been frequent visitors and even the queenlearned to dance within the glorious ballroom” it also boasted the only private royal entranceto the parkas a result of the economic downturn  and  were challenging years with thedecline in travel and tourism in asia impacting most of the hotels in the group jardinematheson a hong kongbased trading conglomerate at that time owned about  of thecompany through jardine strategic holdings for the group’s recent financial performancesee exhibit the group’s executive committee was made up of regional managers and operational headsa majority of the executive management team members were sourced from around the worldwhile customer service functions in each hotel were carried out by local employees to ensurean authentic feel the management team see exhibit  focused primarily on operationalissues the business was operationally intensive in the sense that the hotels’ success dependedon continuous and close attention to detail – the nutsandbolts of service excellence – whichultimately distinguished mandarin oriental hotels’ operations and service delivery from thecompetition source  “mandarin oriental hong kong review” fodor’s website httpwwwfodorscomworldasiachinahongkongreviewhtml  september  source  press quotes mandarin oriental hotel group website httpwwwhubxcomhotelasp  november  mandarin oriental international limited annual report  mandarin oriental hotel group website wwwmandarinorientalcom  november  edouard ettedgui interview by mos project group insead  april  ibid mandarin oriental international limited annual report  mandarin oriental hotel group website wwwmandarinorientalcom  november  “mandarin oriental hyde park” visit london website  httpwwwvisitlondoncomaccommodationdetail  november copyright   insead  strategically edouard ettedgui ceo and two senior directors in the company terry stinsondevelopment director and john witt cfo worked with all individuals who were essentialto making longterm decisions in addition to a topdown strategymaking process thebottomup communication within the organisation created a constant information flow wheregeneral managers and operational heads filtered out and forwarded staff suggestions to themanagement team decisions were communicated via meetings and internal publicationswith several intermediate rounds of backandforth discussions before final decisions weremadethe senior directorsedouard ettedguisince  ettedgui had been ceo of the mandarin oriental hotel group having formerlyserved as finance director in another subsidiary of the parent company jardine mathesongroup a french national and graduate of essec in paris ettedgui had extensive finance andbusiness development experience with major international corporations he was a member ofthe world travel  tourism council and had been appointed advisor on external trade inhong kong by the french government ettedgui was a passionate believer in the totalalignment of all decisions towards growing mandarin oriental into an international luxurybrand including its geographical locations architecture and decor marketing campaignshuman resources and customer service guidelinesjohn wittafter he came on board ettedgui promoted witt a qualified chartered accountant fromcanada with an insead mba degree to be the group’s chief financial officer witt hadextensive international experience in financial planning and control as well as in businessdevelopment in consumer industries ettedgui described him as “a very important businesspartner capable of critical evaluation and lateral thinking he is someone who can go acrossdepartments and bring it back to what it means to the bottom line” witt received his firstdegree a bachelor of commerce from trinity college university of torontoterry stinsonan american lawyer and mechanical engineer by training stinson joined mandarin orientalin  as group development director overseeing the continued development andexecution of new projects around the world he was the group’s most senior representativefrom the us with his vast experience in hotel development and initially as general counselstinson had been central to the group’s growth in ettedgui’s words he was a “very seniorguy” whom others viewed as having substance “you see him you see gravitas”led by ettedgui this trio demonstrated a commitment to establishing mandarin oriental as achain of legendary hotels offering a holistic experience of st century luxury with orientalcharm by defining the corporate brand strategy the three men had always been keenlyobservant of industry developments and were kept well informed by staff members within the edouard ettedgui interview by mos project group insead  april  ibidcopyright   insead  group via small group meetings and collegial communications as the brand’s chiefambassador ettedgui came up with “intuitions” concerning brand strategies based onpersonal analysis witt played the dual role of independently assessing the quality ofettedgui’s intuitions helping him to articulate them as well as to give them economicmeaning he also helped ettedgui identify tradeoffs in the larger scheme of development asa wellrespected industry veteran stinson offered invaluable perspectives within the triothinking through and sketching out potential developments for mandarin oriental hotelsperspectives on the competitionettedgui viewed the luxury hotel segment as fundamentally a growth industry but cyclicaland fragmented the group looked at competitors from two broad dimensions first from astrategic development standpoint four seasons remained the strongest competitor given itssolid brand reputation for customer services its creation of modern luxury and its sustainedtrack record especially in the north america market ritzcarlton recently acquired bymarriott was another major competitor in the luxury hotel segment operating thirdpartyowned hotels under management contracts four seasons and ritzcarlton had achieved areputation for excellent service with extensive global geographical coverage in additionindividual properties such as the carlyle in new york claridges in london and the crillonin paris were also seen as major competitors owing to their historical success as standalonehotels they were often targets for acquisition by development conglomerates or sponsorshipby private equity with the objective of leveraging their brand recognition to expand andgenerate returns to the parent company or investors another group of competitors were thosewith an asian service concept andor similar focus on internationalisation such as shangrila raffles and banyan treesecondly within each destination the group defined five primary competitor hotels basedstrictly on standards of luxury and geographical proximity regardless of the brandthe brandmandarin oriental hotel group’s brand was strongly identified with subdued elegancetraditional oriental values and the concept of “delighting our guests” for the group’sdefinition of “delight” see exhibit “mandarin oriental stood for st century luxury with oriental charm” said ettedgui tohim st century luxury was the right mix of tradition quality and innovation looking at thecompetition consisting of mostly management contractdriven incumbents ettedgui believedthat the group’s ownership or significant interest in hotel properties enabled proprietarycontrol of all aspects of the hotel and its services thereby allowing it to take risks to innovatecustomise and differentiate particularly as “all innovations in the industry came from owneroperated hotels” at mandarin oriental st century luxury was achieved via the use oftechnology food and beverage offerings and the mandarin oriental spa while integratingthe unique sense of place and culture of each destination the group’s hotels reflected orientalcharm in the hospitality experience through subtle asian touches in its dining offerings spaservices decor and staff edouard ettedgui interview by mos project group insead  april  ibidcopyright   insead  mandarin oriental’s strength ultimately derived from the customer’s belief in what the brandstood for ie the guests defined the brand while the perception of a ‘legendary’ hotel wasrather intangible and subjective guests often recalled specific memories or experiences at oneor more hotels when expressing appreciation for the brand these vignettes were often passedon from guest to guest a typical example came from a customer of the terrace restaurant ofthe mandarin oriental hyde park london where “a terrace butler was on hand on hotsummer days with a selection of sunscreens cooling iced towers water sprays and sunglassescleaning service…” furthermore ettedgui and his team believed that generations of localpatrons were central to mandarin oriental’s two legendary hotels in hong kong andbangkok the hotel lobby and its adjacent captain’s bar at mandarin oriental hong kongwere popular meeting venues for local senior executives and decision makers while theclipper lounge on its mezzanine floor was one of hong kongs most popular places for hightea among local socialites and ladies of societywhile each and every mandarin oriental hotel delivered exceptional services ettedguibelieved that building and enhancing the brand was the only way to fully capture andarticulate the value of the collective strengths of all mandarin oriental hotels with theultimate aspiration of creating a brand that stood for ‘legendary’ hotels the management teamaligned corporate strategy at every customer touchpoint to strengthen global brand recognitionvia building critical mass developing a more balanced geographical coverage and leveragingcore competencies and heritageunder the leadership of ettedgui the group underwent international expansion from its hotels in  with a plan to establish more than  rooms in a portfolio of more than hotels around the world over the next few years for the group’s development timeline seeexhibit  according to witt as the management team grew the brand on the basis of the‘legendary’ image the team would manage it “as a luxury brand rather than a hotel brand”highly brand focused it evaluated new hotel projects based on whether they “have thepotential to be a legendary hotel in the community or its resort over time and have the abilityto add value to the existing hotels”at mandarin oriental the food and beverage offerings the spas and the consistent delivery ofexceptional service enabled the brand to communicate to two target audiences the localcommunity and travellers over time the brand as a whole had become far greater than thesum of these individual elementsfood  beverage offeringscontrary to the generic industry model whereby hotel restaurants were mainly a cost centrefor the purpose of servicing guests mandarin oriental had both the capability and the ettedgui edouard “the way forward” mandarin oriental group internal publication  “city restaurant pops up in temporary english garden” july   springwise newsletter website httpspringwisecomweeklyhtm  september  “meeting lobbies” kiwi collection website httpwwwkiwicollectioncomsensationssectionitem  december  oriental travel website httpwwworientaltravelcomhotelcitydetmandarinorientalhtm  december  john witt interview by jessica zee and gabriel szulanski insead  june  ibidcopyright   insead  tradition of running good restaurants in its hotels many of which had over time becomepopular in the local community for regular dining such as business lunches betweenexecutives social meals among friends and family as well as celebratory events like weddingbanquets it was not uncommon to find at least two restaurants in each of its hotels thatcatered to the varying needs of international travellers as well as to a local clienteleconsistent delivery of exceptional servicethe management team saw exceptional service as the “crux of everything” the essentialingredient for any hotel to become legendary the group had come a long way from verballyhanding down service traditions to sharing written standards among individual hoteloperations and now to measuring performance via a proprietary standard – legendaryquality experiences lqe over time the group incorporated guest feedbackcommissioned detailed consumer research and hired professionals to define elegant yetauthentic service with the help of cuttingedge technology and rigorously trained staff toensure consistent delivery of exceptional servicethe spa at mandarin orientala definitive brand identifier championed by ettedgui in  – the development of the spa atmandarin oriental – was aligned with the company’s goal of providing “st century luxurywith oriental charm” its brand heritage and name as spas were already very much part ofthe culture in thailand india japan and china at that time spas typically existed in resortdestinations not the urban locations where mandarin oriental and its competitors operatedduring a threeweek trip to northern india with their wives ettedgui and his team wereintroduced to and experienced ayurvedic spa and yoga they assessed the validity andfeasibility of implementing the spa experience in every mandarin oriental hotel andconsidered whether or not to ultimately incorporate the spa experience into the brandwhile spas were costly to build and had a generally lower return rate per unit area than that ofhotel rooms ettedgui saw their potential to attract customers who would pay a premium for aquality spa service and more importantly choose to stay at the hotel specifically for the spaexperience equally if defined and implemented well spas could be a unique tangible andcredible element of mandarin oriental’s holistic ambience and experience that would furtherdistinguish the brand from its competitors enabling it to attract a leisure audience and furtherheighten its prestigeleveraging this thinking mandarin oriental bangkok’s existing spa operation the world’sfirst wellknown hotel spa and experts recruited from the spa industry the spa at mandarinoriental was built to provide an exclusive highly personalised and holistic approach towellness in a generous space offering therapies including chinese ayurvedic and europeanalternative treatments from yoga to pilates impressive heat and water therapies privaterelaxation spa cuisine and bespoke spa products it was well known that “one does not cometo the mandarin oriental spa for a quick onehour appointment” the spa offered “time edouard ettedgui interview by mos project group insead  april  ibid “like mother like daughter” condé nast traveller february copyright   insead  rituals” and “journey experiences akin to a rite of passage” over the years the spa atmandarin oriental had become a prominent yet integral part of the holistic hospitalityexperience they were regularly featured in various media particularly those with a luxuryleisure audience further enhancing the group’s appeal to travellers around the world and tothe local communitynext stop …new yorkever since its inception the group had strongly focused on a real estatedriven strategyowning a significant equity share in its hotels while ettedgui believed that control over theproperties allowed management to take risks and innovate which was key to the success ofany luxury brand he made it his mandate to fully leverage the power of the brand and todevelop mandarin oriental at the international level executing this mandate was particularlychallenging at the beginning as the group had a limited brand profile outside asia the orderof expansion into new geographical boundaries was unclear and it was unfamiliar withspecific locations to ettedgui north america was a major market in which the company hadto strengthen its overall corporate presence in order to become an international brand thatwas strong both within and outside asia it was therefore logical that this market became thefocus of mandarin oriental’s first global branding campaign as a destination new york wasabsolutely essential not only was it among the world’s top three cities but it was also thecentre of the luxury media industry at the time ettedgui noted “new york is also an important feeder market for mandarin oriental hotel group’s properties manhattan is achieving exceptionally high occupancies and rates within the luxury hotel sector with limited additional room supply anticipated in the near future”the management team asked themselves several key questions how would the flagship hotelin new york be developed what were the absolute essentials of the brand what woulddefine mandarin oriental new york regarding the first question the management team hadtwo potential options to acquire and transform an existing hotel or to work with a developerto build a brand new hotel in reality the availability of prime location sites or propertieswould very much drive the decision the latter questions were more abstract and a delicatebalance would need to be achieved between the two to the management team all threequestions were intertwinedconceiving mandarin oriental new yorkmandarin oriental group aimed to preserve the core brand values of its holistic hospitalityexperience in new york however it was unclear how it would be received in new york adestination that was far removed from asia both in terms of culture and distance anotherunknown was how mandarin oriental could succeed as a brand with a “very limited brand ibid ettedgui edouard “the way forward” mandarin oriental group internal publication  “mandarin oriental announces luxury hotel in new york”  september  the mandarin oriental website wwwmandarinorientalcom  september copyright   insead  profile outside of asia” would mandarin oriental new york be able to become a legendaryhotel appealing to local patrons in new york like its counterparts in bangkok and hongkong this was another uncertaintywhile the importance of consistent delivery of exceptional service was indisputablereplicating mandarin oriental’s very own exceptional service model was consideredimpossible by many from outside of the group based on their belief that cheap labour costs inasia was the precondition for this model – labour costs were known to be high in new yorkin addition a quick scan of factors such as dining and leisure habits in new york at that timerevealed potential differences in the perception of hotel restaurants and spas as outlinedbelowin asia restaurants had been much better integrated into hotels generating revenues fromlocal patrons as well as travelers whereas in new york restaurants in luxury hotels wereoffered as a service to guests rather than a serious part of hotel operations at worst they wereseen as a “necessary evil” and tended to be viewed as cost centres the best restaurants werenot to be found in hotels because hoteliers focused mainly on international travellers whotypically went to the hotel restaurant for breakfastfurthermore introducing the spa concept would be controversial at the time full urban spaswere a new concept to new york and involved expensive investment in terms of propertyspace and operating costs stinson as development director shared the views of mostproperty developers his priority was to extract maximum value from every investment whileacknowledging the mandarin oriental spa as an important brand identifier he was concernedabout the high costs involved and the uncertain return from the spa business in this very newmarkethowever ettedgui was passionate about introducing the full brand experience to new yorkhe was also confident that travellers would be willing to pay a premium for a quality spaexperience and that the spa would attract leisure business from both locals and travellers whowould otherwise not come to the hotel at all in his view in the scheme of building legendaryhotels the hotel’s reputation would ultimately depend upon leisure customers rather thancorporate travellers the full spa offering in an urban setting would be particularly importantin attracting the right customers to this key destination it would also help position the hotelin the local community as the fullness of the experience would also attract local patronsas ettedgui walked to the conference room to meet the rest of the team in preparation for theupcoming discussion with potential developers in new york he wondered how mandarinoriental new york would ultimately be defined john witt interview by jessica zee and gabriel szulanski insead  october copyright   insead  exhibit mandarin oriental hotel group’s recent financial performancesource mandarin oriental international limited annual report  mandarin oriental websitewwwmandarinorientalcom  november copyright   insead  exhibit  mandarin oriental hotel group executive committee as of source case writers created based on the mandarin oriental hotel group’s our personnel webpage at themandarin oriental hotel group websitecopyright   insead  exhibit  mandarin oriental hotel group brand missionmandarin orientals mission is to completely delight and satisfy its guests it is committed to makinga difference every day and continually getting better to stay the best the following are mandarinoriental’s guiding principles delighting our guests we will strive to understand our client and guest needs by listening to their requirements and responding in a competent accurate and timely fashion we will design and deliver our services and products to address their needs in fact we are committed to exceeding their expectations by surprising them with our ability to anticipate and fulfil their wishes working together as colleagues we will emphasize the sharing of responsibility accountability and recognition through a climate of teamwork by working together as colleagues and by treating each other with mutual respect and trust we will all contribute to the groups overall success more productively than if we worked alone promoting a climate of enthusiasm we are committed to everyone at mandarin oriental by providing a caring motivating and rewarding environment as an industry leader we are committed to bringing out the best in our people through effective training and meaningful career and personal development and by encouraging individuality and initiative being the best we will be an innovative leader in the hotel industry and will continually improve our products and services we will seek from our suppliers the highest quality products and services at the best value delivering shareholder value we are committed to being a growing company our successes will result in investment returns which are consistently among the best in the hotel industry playing by the rules we will maintain integrity fairness and honesty in both our internal and external relationships and will consistently live up to our commitments acting with responsibility we will actively participate in the improvement of the environment just as we will be responsible members of our communities and industry organizations source our brand and guiding principles mandarin oriental website httpwwwmandarinorientalcomaboutmoourbranddelight  november copyright   insead  exhibit mandarin oriental hotels development timeline mandarin oriental hong kong the excelsior hong kong mandarin oriental bangkok mandarin oriental manila mandarin oriental jakarta mandarin oriental macau mandarin oriental san francisco and singapore mandarin oriental hyde park london mandarin oriental kuala lumpur mandarin oriental in geneva miami and munich elbow beach bermuda mandarin oriental new york mandarin oriental chiang mai and washington dc mandarin oriental tokyo and the landmark hong kong mandarin oriental prague mandarin oriental in boston and mexico  beyond mandarin oriental in barcelona beijing chicago costa rica grand cayman g